<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Home Affairs Committee Inquiry: Police and Crime Commissioners – progress to date</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:14pt">Written evidence from the </span><br /><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:14pt">Association of Police and Crime Commissioners</span><span style="font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:14pt"> [PCC Progress 34]</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Association of Police and Crime Commissioners (APCC) is the national body which supports Police and Crime Commissioners (‘PCCs’) and other local policing bodies.  This document </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">co-ordinates </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the views of PCC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in relation to the key areas listed in the terms of reference. The document is arranged in line with those key areas.  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Oral evidence was given to the Home Affairs Select Committee by Sir Graham Bright, Tony Lloyd and Ron Ball on the 26</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> November 2013.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 54pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">PCCs can maintain and increase public confidence in policing. PCCs are working hard to ensure local communities have a stronger voice in policing. Working with Chief Constables PCCS are transforming the way forces interact with the public so that policing in the 21</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">st</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> century is more responsive to communities’ concerns about crime.</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Declaration of interests</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:18pt; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 54pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Association of Police and Crime Commissioners (APCC) is a company limited by guarantee. The APCC services are overseen and directed by PCCs. </span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The effectiveness of commissioners in reducing crime and delivering an effective police service within their police force area</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A key role for PCCs is to ensure that the public and victims have a stronger voice in policing. PCCs’ policing and crime plans demonstrate how they are doing this, by putting local community and victims needs at the heart of their vision.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> As a result of consultation policing and crime plans reflect the views and interests of the communities they represent.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Keeping crime low is central to public confidence in policing and PCCs remain vigilant about reducing crime and holding their forces to account to ensure this happens in practice.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> However, it’s important to note that reducing crime isn’t about the police alone.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Over the next year PCCs will be taking on much wider responsibilities for local criminal justice matters, i.e. wider commissioning of services.  This will play an increasingly important role in how PCCs reduce crime and deliver an effective </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">criminal justice </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">service</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, including policing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Crime has continued to fall since PCCs came into office, down 5-7% on the previous year and is now at record low levels with a national decline in reduction of violent crime.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> There is some evidence of a nascent increase in some forms of crime, for example shoplifting and theft from the person. There is also an increase in sexual offences in some areas although this has been</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> attributed to a rise in reporting historic crimes.</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t’s important to note that a comparison of pre-PCC and post-PCC crime statistics will not be available until early 2014.</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Although it is still early in the piece to judge overall effectiveness there are already plenty of examples of PCCs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, both individually and collectively,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> demonstrating their ability to effect positive change in reducing crime and delivering an effective police service.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The following provides a snapshot of initiatives introduced by PCCS to reduce crime and deliver a more effective police service:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Victims of Crime:</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Office of Victims of Crime</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> – Creation of an Office of Victim Service to secure the provision of practical and emotional support to innocent victims of crime (Richard Rhodes, Cumbria)</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Alcohol and drug misuse:</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Drug and alcohol strategy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> – Tackling drug and alcohol crime and misuse through the development of a strategy which seeks to integrate local alcohol based initiatives (Tony Hogg, Devon and Cornwall)</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Mental health:</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 72pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Embedding mental health professionals</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> - Mental health nurses working alongside police officers (Martyn Underhill, Dorset)</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 72pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Response teams</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> - Mental health round-the-clock response teams – </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Matthew Ellis, Staffordshire</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">)</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Rural Crime:</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 72pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Rural Crime Plan</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> - Publishing of a rural crime plan with community input to provide a link between PCSO’s, Special Constables and rural communities (Winston Roddick, North Wales)</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Strengthening </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">ural crime response </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">- Tackling offenders who target farms and rural communities by strengthening response to rural crime (Tim Passmore, Suffolk)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The role of commissioners in holding their chief constables to account   </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">4.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">While there have been some local issues, the vast majority</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of PCCs and Chief Constables have constructive and robust relationships as characterized by oral evidence given to the Committee by both PCCs and Chief Constables. While there is a clear line of accountability from chief constables to directly elected PCCs this does not cut across their operational independence.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">4.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Policing Protocol Order 2011 states:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 82.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Chief constables remain operationally independent.</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 82.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Commissioner</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> must not fetter the operational independence of the police force and the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">chief constable who leads it.</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:12pt; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 82.49pt; padding-left:7.51pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">etermination of Parliament and of the Home Secretary that the operational independence of the chief constable must be inviolate.</span></li></ul></ul></ul><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 90pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">4.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The role of PCCs in holding chief constables to account is characterized by transparency and rigour. A good example is Cambridgeshire which holds a Business Co-ordination Board (BCB), a monthly meeting between the Commissioner, Deputy Commissioner, ACPO rank officers and senior officers of the OPCC. This is a forum in which current and future business is discussed between the senior leaders of the two bodies, focussing on issues relating to strategy, governance, business and holding the Chief Constable to account. It </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is one forum in which decisions can be made by the Commissioner, informed by the decision making policy. Minutes of the meeting and key papers are published on the Commissioner’s website.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">4.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Surrey PCC has instituted live webcasts of bi-monthly management meetings so that the public can see how he is holding the Chief Constable to account and the progress that is being made.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The role of police and crime panels in holding their commissioners to account</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">5.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The role of the P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">olice and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rime </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">anel</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">scrutinise</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the PCC in the delivery of their</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">functions whereas it is the role of the electorate to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">hold the PCC to account</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">5.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The powers of the Panel </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> set out in legislation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">; the legislation does not provide for any other forum for scrutiny</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  It is for Parliament to consider any change to those </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">owers. PCCs will of course have an interest but respect the Panel’s independent and distinct role in scrutinising PCCs.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Indeed PCCs remain committed to PCPs taking full advantage of their existing powers. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">5.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Police and Crime Panels have o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nly been operational for one year</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and there are indications of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">growing engagement between PCCs and Panels</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he relationships </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">b</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">etween Panels and PCCs are maturing, and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> there are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> areas of effective discussions around difficult issues of budgeting and the precept.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> PCCS believe that the relationship with the Panel is an important one and value the potential for a “candid friend” in the development of policy.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">5.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Greater Manchester provides a good example of a PCP making use of its powers of scrutiny through an effective panel comprising 10 local authority leaders. The work of the panel is underpinned by a police and crime steering group which has been able to work jointly with police on achieving consensus where there have previously been diverging views.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">5.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There should be r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ecogni</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tion</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that the change from the Police Authority system took place very swiftly, with limited transitional planning, mid-financial year, making conversations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> particularly those about budget-making decisions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> challenging for both PCCs and Panels.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">5.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In conclusion PCCS believe that PCPS are well placed to scrutinise the delivery of their functions and that as they mature they are increasingly making full use of their existing powers.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The division of functions and staff between commissioners and chief constables following the Stage 2 transfers under the Police Reform and Social Responsibility Act 2011</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">6.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">underlying intention of Stage 2 is that operational staff under the control and direction of Chief Constables will pass to their employment.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">PCCs retain responsibility for the budget and holding forces to account. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">6.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">No one force’s Stage 2 plan is exactly the same as another.  There are variations in what each PCC proposes, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> some keeping a larger number of staff than others and some keeping functions which others are not.  PCCs and chief constables are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">deciding</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> locally </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">what is best for their forces, ultimately to reduce crime and deliver an effective police service.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">6.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Although all Stage 2 plans are different it is possible to say that most plans will see the majority of police staff transferring to the employment of the Chief Constable, whilst the PCC will continue to employ a small body of support staff to help run their offices and support them in their oversight and scrutiny functions. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">6.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">All </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">plans</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are still subject to the approval of the Home Secretary and we expect confirmation of plans from December, in time for implementation in April 2014.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The role of commissioners in budget and precept setting </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">7.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Commissioners have maintained progress on working with chief constables to bring down the cost of policing in line with the government's targets, without so far a significant adverse impact on performance and crime levels. This has been achieved through efficiency and capacity enhancements, reductions in bureaucracy, and more robust scrutiny and challenge. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">But it would be wrong to suggest that austerity has not posed a significant challenge for leaders of the police service.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">7.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It should be noted that HMIC has identified an increased number of forces where further reductions may risk services delivered to the public.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">7.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">While</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> significant success has been achieved through collaboration, better procurement, and more efficient use of staff resources, looking ahead, substantial further grant reductions are likely.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The scope to cut costs is not infinite, and Commissioners </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">need</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the government to work with them to consider the long term configuration of services and resourcing levels which will ensure that services remain sustainable. There is also a need to consider better approaches to the management of demands for policing and community services.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">7.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In year 1, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the vast majority of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Commissioners have set precepts which have been at or</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">below the government's threshold. While recognising the need to control local taxation levels, PCCs were elected on the basis of clear statements about local plans and priorities. There is a powerful case for arguing that the stringent controls on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">precept</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> increases should be relaxed where the increase is linked to delivering additional services requested by communities. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">7.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Ultimately, PCCs are responsible for the safety of their communities. As the austerity </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">agenda </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">continue</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, there may come a point in some areas where the Force is unable to sustain current levels of services and expectations within </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> resources available from grant and the target level of Council Tax.  PCCs will be monitoring performance locally, and this could trigger the need for increases in Council Tax above the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">threshold.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">7.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Should any Commissioner wish to raise the precept above the stated threshold they would need licence from their </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">communities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (via a referendum) and they would need to consider the cost implications of such a course of action.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">7.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A number of Commissioners have cited concerns about further impacts on their budgets:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The cost to local budgets of top-slicing to facilitate an expanded IPCC.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A reduction in local budgets as a result of top-slicing for the Innovation Fund (thought to be £50 million in 2014/15).</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Implications in 2016 if the Pensions Bill is not amended (additional costs to local budgets could be over £250 million – arising from the abolition of contracted out NI rates).</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">7.8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Commissioners can only deliver through others. In the case of the chief, the PCC can set targets and hold the Force to account. It is not the same with other partners who, by their own actions, can impact on Policing resources. A prime example is in relation to Health, where changes to the way Mental Health care is commissioned, and pressures on Ambulance Services can impact on policing. In situations where an individual is in crisis, such as those placed under Section 136 of the Mental Health Act 1983 and may represent a danger to themselves or others, too often the police service is expected to act as 'last resort' with insufficient support from the health and social care partners who are better placed to deal with the needs of the individual.  PCCs need the power to apply policy or financial levers on these partner services in such circumstances, or there should be a transfer of resources nationally.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The effectiveness of commissioners in promoting local policing priorities</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">8.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This is one of the areas where PCCs have been able to demonstrate a clear difference over the system that preceded them. PCCs are more engaged and better recognised by their local communities. They communicate and consult more with the local community and as such their agenda better reflects the priorities of local people. Whilst only 7% of the public were aware that they could go to their police authority if they were unhappy with their policing (Cabinet Office Research 2007), a ComRes poll for the BBC revealed that 62% of the public are aware of the work of PCCs.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> PCCs are achieving this greater recognition as a result of the level of engagement with their communities. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">8.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">PCCs can demonstrate substantial engagement with their local communities. The Staffordshire PCC for example has engaged face to face with over 12,000 people in Staffordshire since 1 January 2013.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">8.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">PCCs are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">progressing good work to promote their local policing priorities. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Below </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">provides a summary of the most often mentioned PCC’s individual key priorities in police and crime plans:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Public Safety - Make the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ublic feel safe (41)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Anti-social Behaviour - Tackle, reduce and prevent ASB (30)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Offender Management - Tackle and reduce re-offending (24)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Victims – Provide the necessary support and protection (20)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Community – Support, respond to and protect vulnerable people (12)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Offender Management – Increase the number of offenders brought to justice (11)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Alcohol and Drugs related behaviour - Reduce the impact of alcohol related crime and disorder (11)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Domestic abuse – Tackle domestic abuse / violence (11)</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">8.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In Cambridgeshire the following initiative have been undertaken in response to local priorities:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">An operation to educate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> cyclists about</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> anti-social cycling and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> enforce</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> cycling offences to make Cambridge safer for all road users</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> clamp down on crime and to reduce road deaths and casualties amongst cyclists.  </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A Neighbourhood Alert system which allows messages to be targeted at street level to members of the public who subscribe by email allowing Neighbourhood Watch and Cambridgeshire Constabulary to talk directly to the people they need to, when they need to.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A new system to allow partners to share information relating to anti-social behaviour enables a joined up approach and response to these</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> local priority</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> issues</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.51pt; padding-left:4.49pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Progress on establishing collaboration agreements with other commissioners, policing organisations and partners</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">9.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Collaboration is one of a number of areas of focus, and experience shows that collaboration projects are often a big commitment of resources while they are being planned, and often take time to produce real benefits. Many forces are focusing on ensuring that they are as efficient as possible before undertaking more ambitious collaboration projects.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">9.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">PCCs are collaborating well with other PCCs. In the South West for example PCCs meet every six weeks and have already approved three collaborative ventures. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">9.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Whilst fully recognising the value of collaboration, Commissioners are focused on the here and now, and the really big savings on budgets at this time still come from reducing directly employed staff levels, and increasing the efficiency of those that remain.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">9.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Although focussed on the here and now there are great examples of PCCs reaping the benefits of sharing resources with different agencies. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">For example, t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he co-location of services where</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">police, council and health workers are all based in the same building</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> generates</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> modest financial benefits </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">but also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">has a much more fundamental benefit of getting agencies to work better in partnership which feeds into the strategic overview of reducing crime and reducing demand.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">9.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is a long list of examples of where collaboration is successfully progressing. These include</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">: </span></p><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Integration of Forces (Warwickshire/ West Mercia)</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">National Police Air Service (mandated collaboration - all PCCs led by West Yorkshire)</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Collaboration of a number of policing functions -major crime, forensics, firearms, procurement, fleet, insurance and risk and latterly serious crime (Surrey/Sussex)</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Regional Policing units (Yorkshire and Humber/ East Midlands)</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Shared support teams (Humberside and South Yorkshire);</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Proposals for shared infrastructure with Fire (Suffolk) </span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Blue light collaboration (Dorset and Humberside)</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Statements of intent on Fire integration (Includes N Yorkshire / Northants)</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Collaboration on serious crime, IT and support services (Kent and Essex)</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Sharing network services (telecoms technology) (Thames Valley, Hampshire, Surrey)</span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Business partnering involving support services as well as control room and criminal justice services (Lincolnshire / Cleveland) </span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 65.6pt; padding-left:6.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Integrated business support services with local authority partners (Avon and Somerset)</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.45pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">9.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Work will continue on collaboration with local, regional and national partners and with the public and private sectors to maintain the momentum on collaboration and generate efficiencies and value for money for our communities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Transparency of and reporting by commissioners to date</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">10.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">PCCs take transparency very seriously and equate this with empowering communities to hold them to account effectively.  Many have taken steps to improve information about both themselves and the force – for instance, Ian Johnston, PCC in Gwent has launched a PCC App to inform the public about what he is doing, and Sue Mountstevens, PCC in Avon and Somerset, has launched an on-line ‘track my crime’ service for victims.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">10.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">PCCs are now publishing their expenses and other related information appropriately.  No national register has been created, in part because of the bureaucracy and complexity involved, but also because most PCCs feel that this is a matter of local accountability. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">10.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In addition to equality and diversity within their own offices, PCCs also have a duty to ensure their forces are compliant with their equality duties and that they adhere to the relevant guidance on employment processes and procedures, including recruitment and retention. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">10.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">All PCCs have now completed their annual registration as Data Controllers, but in any event, the transition provisions in the PRSRA meant PCCs were covered by the former police authority registrations.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">10.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Mechanisms to check the accuracy of crime data are in place in all forces, but PCCs are not complacent and know that more can be done.  The current thematic inspection of data integrity by HMIC will be an important step in informing PCCs what more should be done – although several have already put additional steps in place.  For instance, Nick Alston in Essex is setting up an integrity committee, whose terms of reference will include checking force data independently.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Association of Police and Crime Commissioners</span></p><p style="margin:6pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:18pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:18pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>